ken-main-surface-secondary px-4 py-2 text-xs font-sans justify-between rounded-t-md"><span>sql</span><span class="" data-state="closed"><button class="flex gap-1 items-center"><svg width="24" height="24" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" class="icon-sm"><path fill-rule="evenodd" clip-rule="evenodd" d="M12 4C10.8954 4 10 4.89543 10 6H14C14 4.89543 13.1046 4 12 4ZM8.53513 4C9.22675 2.8044 10.5194 2 12 2C13.4806 2 14.7733 2.8044 15.4649 4H17C18.6569 4 20 5.34315 20 7V19C20 20.6569 18.6569 22 17 22H7C5.34315 22 4 20.6569 4 19V7C4 5.34315 5.34315 4 7 4H8.53513ZM8 6H7C6.44772 6 6 6.44772 6 7V19C6 19.5523 6.44772 20 7 20H17C17.5523 20 18 19.5523 18 19V7C18 6.44772 17.5523 6 17 6H16C16 7.10457 15.1046 8 14 8H10C8.89543 8 8 7.10457 8 6Z" fill="currentColor"></path></svg>Copy code</button></span></div><div class="p-4 overflow-y-auto"><code class="!whitespace-pre hljs language-sql"><span class="hljs-keyword">DELETE</span> <span class="hljs-keyword">FROM</span> login
<span class="hljs-keyword">WHERE</span> Accounttype <span class="hljs-operator">=</span> <span class="hljs-string">'investor'</span>
<span class="hljs-keyword">AND</span> <span class="hljs-keyword">NOT</span> <span class="hljs-keyword">EXISTS</span> (
    <span class="hljs-keyword">SELECT</span> <span class="hljs-number">1</span>
    <span class="hljs-keyword">FROM</span> information_investor
    <span class="hljs-keyword">WHERE</span> information_investor.investor_id <span class="hljs-operator">=</span> login.id
);
</code></div></div></pre><p>This query performs the following actions:</p><ul><li>It selects entries from the <code>login</code> table where the <code>Accounttype</code> is 'investor'.</li><li>For each of these entries, it checks if a corresponding entry exists in the <code>information_investor</code> table (where the <code>investor_id</code> matches the <code>id</code> from the <code>login</code> table).</li><li>If no matching entry is found in the <code>information_investor</code> table, it means the investor does not have information in the <code>information_investor</code> table, and thus, their login details are deleted.</li></ul><h3>Important Considerations</h3><ul><li><strong>Backup Data</strong>: Before running a delete operation, especially one that can potentially affect multiple rows, it's crucial to backup your database. This way, you can restore data if something goes wrong.</li><li><strong>Testing</strong>: Test the query in a safe, non-production environment to ensure it works as expected and only deletes the intended data.</li><li><strong>Foreign Key Constraints</strong>: If there are foreign key constraints with cascade delete actions linked to the <code>login</code> table, deleting an investor could also delete related data in other tables. Review and understand your database's foreign key constraints and how they're configured before proceeding.</li><li><strong>Transactional Safety</strong>: Consider wrapping your delete operation in a transaction if your database system supports it (like PostgreSQL, MySQL with InnoDB, etc.). This way, if part of the operation fails, you can roll back the entire transaction to maintain database integrity.</li></ul></div></div></div><div class="mt-1 flex justify-start gap-3 empty:hidden"><div class="text-gray-400 flex self-end lg:self-center justify-center lg:justify-start mt-0 -ml-1 h-7 visible"><span class="" data-state="closed"><button class="flex items-center gap-1.5 rounded-md p-1 text-xs text-token-text-terti